<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 13. Explaining the Ruffles Layout for the Front of the Skirt.</h1>
<p><strong>It is time to start decorating the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I will start from the front half – the half-circle face piece. It will be decorated with ruffles and, mind you, those ruffles will have no seams on them. </strong></p>
<p><strong>A regular ruffle</strong> is a rectangular piece of fabric gathered along one of its longer sides. The gathered edge is then sewn to the garment and you can always see the seam allowance. No matter how neatly you do this, it will always be noticeable on a see-through skirt.</p>
<p><strong>My ruffle will also be made of a rectangular piece of fabric. Only this time, the rectangle will be folded in half and gathered along the middle (i.e. the fold line). </strong>I will then spread it open and sew it on the garment by following the gathering stitches. After I sew the ruffle on, its top half will fall down upon its bottom half. <strong>It will be a double ruffle with no seam allowance. </strong>Such ruffles are easy to make and I use them quite widely.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20skirts/mermaid%20wedding%20skirt/Tutorial%2013.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>There are certain rules you should stick to when making double ruffles like this. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Firstly, </strong>veiling ruffles must be cut on the cross because it is easier to gather veiling neatly in this direction.</p>
<p><strong>Secondly, </strong>I will not sew the prepared strips of veiling in a single long strip. And that already makes the work much easier. Each strip will be gathered individually but, whenever there is 5-10cm left before the end of the strip, I will put down the next one, and continue gathering. This means the strips will be joined by the gathering stitches. I won’t join them along their vertical edged. And this will only make the skirt fuller.</p>
<p><strong>The fact that the skirt features a train makes the process a little more complicated. </strong></p>
<p><strong>If it were a plain half-circle skirt </strong>with the same length all around, I would arrange the ruffles in even parallel rows going from down to up.</p>
<p><strong>But the length of a skirt with a train naturally varies: from 79cm along the front in our case to 120cm along the princess seams. </strong>Thus while the top ruffle will reach the top edge of the skirt at the front, there will be an uncovered area along the princess seam of a length equal to the difference between the above-mentioned lengths, i.e. 41cm. This uncovered area will have to be filled with shorter ruffles gradually decreasing in length toward the top. And you must by no means do this! The ruffles will all go at different angles; they will start sticking up and spoil the overall look of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong>Here is what I offer instead: I will carefully redistribute everything in the area of the skirt where the ruffles are not parallel to each other. </strong></p>
<p><strong>And I need to decide on the size of the ruffles themselves before I can start marking the suggested guidelines on the half-circle skirt with a train with certain values and parameters. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The ready ruffle will have a width of 12.5cm. </strong>This means I need to cut strips of veiling with a width of 25cm. You can, of course, cut your ruffles with a different width depending on your vision of the skirt. I will say how much veiling I have used after finishing all work.</p>
<p><strong>So I start marking guidelines on a half of my half-circle skirt. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20skirts/mermaid%20wedding%20skirt/Tutorial%2013.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The first ruffle will be positioned 5cm above the bottom edge of the skirt. </strong>As you remember, the bottom edge is supposed to stay 4cm above floor level at the front of the skirt (5.5cm including the seam allowance).</p>
<p>If I put the bottom ruffle with a width of 12.5cm five centimeters above the bottom edge of the skirt, then the bottom edge of the ruffle will stay 2cm above floor level. There is nothing bad about it since veiling ruffles usually tend to bob up and down anyway. Besides, I will add a small allowance to the front length of the skirt so I can balance it out with respect to the back length.</p>
<p>You can always trim the ruffle at the final fitting. It would be a lot worse if it turned out to be too narrow.</p>
<p><strong>Let me highlight it again that the length of the dress is determined by the front length of the skirt! </strong></p>
<p><strong>So the first bottom ruffle (1) will run parallel to the bottom edge of the skirt and 5cm above it. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Then I will step 5cm from ruffle (1) up along the princess seam line and put down a short ruffle (2) which will stop at the intersection with ruffle (1). </strong></p>
<p><strong>Ruffle (3)</strong> will start from the centre front line. It will first go parallel to ruffle (1) and then, as it gets past the intersection of ruffles (1) and (2), it will start going parallel to ruffle (2).</p>
<p><strong>Then I will step another 5cm up along the princess seam line and put down another short ruffle (4) which will stop at the intersection with ruffle (3). </strong></p>
<p>It is advisable not to keep the intersection points of short and long ruffles at the same level. You will create a more beautiful pattern by placing them at random.</p>
<p><strong>I continue drawing the rest of the guidelines in the same fashion. </strong></p>
<p><strong>So there will be eight long ruffles going through the centre front line: ruffles (1), (3), (5), (7), (9), and (11).</strong> All these ruffles will be placed at 5cm intervals, meaning that the last one will go cross the centre front line at 40cm from the bottom edge of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong>There will be 39cm left between the top ruffle and the top edge along the centre front line. </strong></p>
<p><strong>79cm – 40cm = 39cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>There will be sixteen ruffles, numbered (1) to (16), going from the princess seam lines.</strong> Eight of them will be long (odd numbers) and another eight will be short (even numbers). All ruffles will be placed at 5cm intervals, which means the last ruffle will start 80cm from the bottom edge of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong>There will be 40cm left between the top ruffle and the top edge along the centre front line.</strong></p>
<p><strong>120cm – 80cm = 40cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>This way I have basically evened out the distance between the top ruffle and the top edge along the centre front line and the princess seam line (the difference is as little as 1cm) so all other ruffles can run parallel to each other. </strong>Two of the ruffles will be positioned at an interval of 4cm along the centre front line.</p>
<p><strong>I will put short ruffles at the bottom of the skirt</strong> because it will be less noticeable. There are also certain advantages to using these short ruffles: they will create a unique pattern on the skirt making it even more beautiful.</p>
<p><strong>All ruffles will start and stop 2cm from the stay-stitching made along the princess seam lines. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Using a disappearing ink pen, I will transfer the ruffles layout on the face of the skirt with the hem already reinforced with soft Rigilene boning. </strong>I will fold the skirt in half, draw the layout on the first half, and then transfer it on the other half (the guidelines will show through). If you work at a slow pace, you can transfer the layout on the fabric area after area starting from the bottom.</p>
<p><strong>I will draw several inclined vertical lines (marked blue) for additional control </strong>to draw the arc-shaped guidelines more neatly and maintain precise intervals between them (5cm).</p>
<p>This will help me achieve smoother guidelines and the whole layout will be more precise.</p>
<p><strong>I will put ruffles on the skirt moving from down to up. It is easier this way. </strong></p>
<p><strong>And I will work in the following order: </strong>I will cut strips of veiling with a width of 25cm, gather them along the middle with a ruffler presser-foot, and put them on the skirt in accordance with the layout.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20skirts/mermaid%20wedding%20skirt/Tutorial%2013.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
